These design patterns are implemented using GtkListBox. We may want to differentiate them from cases where GtkTreeView is more appropriate.
Lists are a flexible, general purpose design pattern. As such they come in various different shapes. These patterns illustrate some of the common conventions for how lists can be used.
Selection lists are a special type of list, used to select items. The background of the row is highlighted. Typically used for lists of content items.
Controls can be linked to an "action area" - clicking this activates the control. This is appropriate for switches, check boxes, radio buttons.

Another common pattern is to embed controls in the list rows. Controls like radios, check boxes and switches should be linked to the row background, so that clicking the list row activates the control.
